\begin_layout Abstract
The paper deals with voting rules that require voters to rate the candidates
 on a finite evaluation scale and then elect a candidate whose median grade
 is maximum.
 These rules differ by the way they choose among candidates with the same
 median grade.
 Call proponents (resp.
 opponents) of a candidate the voters who rate this candidate strictly above
 (resp.
 strictly below) her median grade.
 A 
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
natural
\end_layout

\end_inset

simple rule, called the typical judgment, orders tied candidates by the
 difference between their share of proponents and opponents.
 An appealing rule, called the usual judgment, divides this difference by
 the share of median votes.
 An alternative rule, called the central judgment, compares the relative
 shares of proponents and opponents.
 
\begin_inset Note Note
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout
The three new rules are continuous with respect to these shares.
 
\end_layout

\end_inset

The usual judgment is continuous with respect to these shares.
 The majority judgment of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "balinski_theory_2007"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 considers the largest of these shares and loses continuity.
 A result in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "balinski_judge:_2014"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 aims to characterize the majority judgment and states that only a certain
 class of functions share some valuable characteristics, like monotonicity.
 We relativize
\begin_inset Note Note
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout
the paper rightfully points out that the claim doesn’t hold for a finite
 scale (and this is useful, because it says that new tie-breaking rules
 may be considered), but doesn’t really “disprove it”.
 #2
\end_layout

\end_inset

 this result, by emphasizing that it only holds for continuous scales of
 grades.
 Properties remaining specific to the majority judgment in the discrete
 case are idiosyncratic features rather than universally sought criteria,
 and other median-based rules exist that are both monotonic and continuous.
\end_layout

